review: I just finished the book, and I find new meaning for its title. Will is not a coward but he is an absolutist, in a different sense than the term had fI just finished the book, and I find new meaning for its title. Will is not a coward but he is an absolutist, in a different sense than the term had for the British in WWI. His moral judgments are absolute and unwavering, immature. He is only 19, so this is realistic. His principles and emotions are disconnected. His moral certainty comes at the price of dishonesty to himself and others. In contrast, Tristan is in touch with his own ambiguities and suffers because of this. Wounded by Will and by society's intolerance, he also suffers from the vehemence of his own emotions. While the ending surprised me, it also seems in keeping with Tristan's character....more

review: 7 April 2013 27%.I identify with Sue Hendler more than with any other person who has written about cancer, dying, etc. Perhaps because she was writing7 April 2013 27%.I identify with Sue Hendler more than with any other person who has written about cancer, dying, etc. Perhaps because she was writing a series of columns for her local newspaper, her observations are sharp, immediate, and show the vicissitudes we experience. Like me, she is a planner and someone used to being in control. The frustration of being unable to predict, plan, control anything for sure. Change happens daily, even hourly, Strong hunger for more life--I am older so may find it easier to let go, but not by much. We both hate and fear pain and incapacity. We are troubled by needing other people and deeply grateful for all they do for us....more
